35. To sum up, thete were few new lessons learnt, but many old ones received fresh em- phasis. Those which require most firmly to be borne in mind are

(@) The need for boldness and the value of holding even a small highly mobile reserve to exploit success daringly.

(b) The importance of not overestimating the enemy’s resources, exemplified in this case by the infra-red equipment bogey, which led us to lie too far offshore at the initial landings. .

(©) The importance of training in a ser- vice which is no longer manned by a majority of prime seamen, and the need for combined training with the soldiers with’ whom they are to work.

(d) The importance of carrying out such beach reconnaissance as is required well in advance, to gain security.

(©) The vital necessity for immediate in- stallation of a proper air defence system at occupied ports.

@ The need of co-ordination in the various elements of Naval Port Parties who should be assembled and organised under one command before embarkation. __.

(g) The necessity for promulgating experi- enced advice about conditions in a theatre of operations to units’ joining from other stations.
